Substitute: tan3x = [2t/(1 - t²) + t]/[1 - (2t/(1 - t²)) * t] = [ (2t + t(1 - t²))/(1 - t²) ] / [ (1 - t² - 2t²)/(1 - t²) ] = (3t - t³)/(1 - 3t²), which matches our earlier result. Similarly, for n=4, tan4x = tan(3x + x) = [tan3x + tanx]/[1 - tan3x tanx]. Substitute tan3x = (3t - t³)/(1 - 3t²): Numerator: [ (3t - t³)/(1 - 3t²) + t ] = [3t - t³ + t(1 - 3t²)] / (1 - 3t²) = [3t - t³ + t - 3t³]/(1 - 3t²) = (4t - 4t³)/(1 - 3t²) Denominator: 1 - [ (3t - t³)/(1 - 3t²) * t ] = 1 - [ (3t² - t��)/(1 - 3t²) ] = [ (1 - 3t²) - 3t² + t�� ] / (1 - 3t²) = (1 - 6t² + t��)/(1 - 3t²) Therefore, tan4x = (4t - 4t³)/(1 - 6t² + t��). So, the recursion here is that to get tan(nx), we use tan((n-1)x) and tanx. Each time, the coefficients in the numerator and denominator are derived from the previous coefficients.
